    <mainBody>
      <level>
        <content>
          <table uk:widths="3.34in 0.59in 3.24in">
            <tr>
              <td colspan="2">
                <p><b>Title:</b> The Civil Liability (Information Requirements) and Risk Transformation (Amendment) Regulations 2020 </p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p>De minimis assessment</p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td colspan="2">
                <p><b>SI No: Draft Affirmative </b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p><b>Date: 13/01/2020</b></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td colspan="2">
                <p><b>Other departments or agencies:   </b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p><b>Type of regulation:  </b><b>Domestic</b></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td colspan="2">
                <p><b>N/A</b></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p><b>Date measure comes into force:  </b></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td colspan="2">
                <p><b>Contact for enquiries</b>:  Dominic Wheeler, dominic.wheeler@hmtreasury.gov.uk<marker name="tab" /></p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p><b>01/04/2020</b></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p><b>Cost of Preferred (or more likely) Option</b></p>
              </td>
              <td colspan="2" rowspan="2">
                <p><b>Net cost to business per year </b></p>
                <p>(EANDCB in 2014 prices)</p>
                <p><b>n/a (one-off cost)</b></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p><b>£4.7m</b></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <table uk:widths="7.29in">
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p><b>Questions</b></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p><b>1. </b> <b>What is the problem under consideration? Why is government intervention necessary? </b></p>
                <p>The Civil Liability Act 2018 (CLA) reformed the compensation system for whiplash injuries and changed the way the Personal Injury Discount Rate (PIDR) is calculated. These reforms are expected to generate savings for insurers. However, Parliamentarians expressed concerns that these savings would not be passed onto consumers, and requested an amendment to the Act (Section 11) that requires the Government to report to Parliament before 31 March 2025 about (i) whether any cost benefits have been realised as a result of the reforms in the Act;  and (ii) whether and to what extent insurers have passed on savings from the reforms in the Act. Government intervention is therefore necessary to implement this reporting requirement.</p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p><b>2. What </b><b>are the policy objectives and the intended effects?</b></p>
                <p>The wider policy objective is to ensure that pricing practices in motor insurance support effective competition and lead to good consumer outcomes. This specific policy will obligate private motor insurance providers to submit a one-off data submission to the FCA (Financial Conduct Authority) that shows how their costs and premiums have changed since the anticipated implementation of the CLA reforms. They will also be required to calculate and provide figures for the counterfactual (i.e. their costs and premiums had the Act not been passed). The FCA will aggregate the figures from all firms and pass them onto HMT, who will evaluate them and produce a final report. This will give sufficient evidence to Parliamentarians that the benefits of CLA reforms have been passed onto consumers.</p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p><b>3. </b><b>What policy options have been considered, including any alternatives to regulation? Please justify preferred option.</b></p>
                <p>As this is secondary legislation, no other policy options have been considered. Section 11 of the Civil Liability Act 2018 requires the Government to report to Parliament about whether insurers have passed on savings from the reforms in the Act. These regulations fulfil this requirement.</p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p><b>4. </b><b>Please justify why the net impacts (i.e. net costs or benefits) to business will be less than £5 million a year.</b></p>
                <p><u>To do this, please set out the following: </u></p>
                <p>◦ <b>What will businesses have to do differently?  </b></p>
                <p>◦ Firms will need to produce a one-off data return showing whether their costs and premiums have changed over a three-year reporting period (financial years 2020-21, 2021-22, and 2022-2023), and produce counterfactual figures showing costs and premiums for the same period if the Act had not been passed. Details of the expected process are set out in the costings below. These data will be provided to the FCA through a one-off submission by 1st October 2023.</p>
                <p>◦ <b>How many businesses will this impact per year?</b></p>
                <p>◦ The Association of British Insurers (ABI) reports that there are 101 companies underwriting motor insurance that are Motor Insurance Bureau (MIB) members.</p>
                <p>◦ Only insurers that meet the threshold of 100,000 or more motor insurance policies sold in a year within the reporting period will be subject to the reporting requirements of this SI. This threshold was set based on industry responses to the Government consultation (see section 5b). Therefore, the smallest/most specialised insurers are purposively excluded from the reporting requirements.</p>
                <p>◦ Insurers who only offer policies for commercial vehicles will also not fall into scope of the reporting requirements, which only apply to private motor insurance policies issued by firms.</p>
                <p>◦ Since these two groups of insurers will not fall into scope, we estimate that 70-80 individual insurers will be subject to the reporting requirements. This range is intended to capture the uncertainties of individual insurers’ policy sales falling above/below the 100,000 threshold, and of firms going out of business/entering the market within the 3-year reporting period.</p>
                <p>◦ <b>What is the direct cost/benefit per business per year? </b></p>
                <p>◦ The figures and estimations within this impact assessment have been developed with extensive collaboration with relevant external stakeholders: the FCA and the ABI. The calculations in this assessment follow the FCA methodology for calculating compliance costs on the basis of staff time and labour costs (as outlined in <a href="https://www.fca.org.uk/publication/corporate/how-analyse-costs-benefits-policies.pdf"><u>https://www.fca.org.uk/publication/corporate/how-analyse-costs-benefits-policies.pdf</u></a>). The FCA have provided estimates of labour costs and time based on their evidence and experience of compliance cost calculations, and have worked alongside HMT to develop the calculations in this impact assessment. The ABI have provided detail on the number of firms that will be impacted by this SI. Where figures have been provided by external stakeholders, this is indicated below. Both the FCA and ABI have reviewed the final cost estimates and calculations in this assessment, including high/low/best estimates, and are content with them. We believe the level of analysis in this assessment to be proportionate to the cost of the policy.</p>
                <p>◦ Insurers will be required to provide basic information on their premiums and costs for the three years of the reporting period. The FCA advises that this pricing data should be readily available from firms’ existing systems and processes, although up to half of firms may be operating using aged systems that would require manual data extraction. This would represent a cost equivalent to <b>2 weeks</b>’ work by an in-house data analyst paid at £32k p.a. (based on salary average from <a href="https://www.glassdoor.co.uk/Salaries/data-analyst-salary-SRCH_KO0,12.htm"><u>https://www.glassdoor.co.uk/Salaries/data-analyst-salary-SRCH_KO0,12.htm</u></a>), plus non-wage labour costs of 30%.</p>
                <p>◦ We therefore estimate this as a cost of <b>£1.6k </b>paid by <b>50% </b>of firms (32k/52*2*1.3)</p>
                <p>◦ As well as providing actual data, firms will be required to calculate counterfactual data that show costs and premiums had the CLA not been passed. All firms will have to bear this cost, as it is integral to the information reporting requirements. The FCA advises that the actuarial costs for this may comprise a <b>week</b>’s work for 3 actuaries (£66k p.a.) plus senior oversight (£73k p.a.) (salaries taken from Institute and Faculty of Actuaries data,  <a href="https://www.actuaries.org.uk/become-actuary/why-become-actuary/how-much-will-i-earn"><u>https://www.actuaries.org.uk/become-actuary/why-become-actuary/how-much-will-i-earn</u></a>), plus non-wage labour costs of 30%. </p>
                <p>◦ We therefore estimate this cost as <b>£6.8k </b>paid by <b>100% </b>of firms ((66k*3+73k)/52*1.3)</p>
                <p>◦ Firms will be required to have audit oversight to test their processes and outcomes against agreed upon procedures. All firms will need to do this. Based on their rates for skilled persons, the FCA estimates that this will cost £25k plus VAT.</p>
                <p>◦ We therefore estimate this cost as <b>£30k </b>paid by <b>100% </b>of firms</p>
                <p>◦ The FCA advises that firms may engage in governance and risk management procedures.  These governance procedures are not mandated in the legislation. It is likely that a ‘second line of defence’ review will occur at formal governance committees. A large insurer may expect to hold a 2-day risk committee comprising 6 NEDs each paid £2.5k (salary of 100k p.a. for 40 days; FCA estimate) at a cost of <b>£15k. </b>However, small- to medium-sized firms, who are likely to undergo proportionately smaller internal governance procedures, will also be in scope of the reporting requirements.</p>
                <p>◦ To take into account uncertainties around how firms may choose to conduct internal governance, this assessment estimates that <b>100% </b>of firms will go through governance processes, at an <i>average</i> cost per firm of <b>£7.5k </b>(low estimate)<b>, £10k </b>(mid estimate), or <b>£12.5k </b>(high estimate) </p>
                <p>◦ Some firms may further seek external legal advice to confirm that their data returns comply with the legislation. The FCA estimates that this process may cost approximately the same as the external audit procedure. This is a discretionary spend, and is not mandated in the legislation. It is uncertain how many firms will seek external legal advice; however, given that data returns will have already undergone scrutiny/oversight from actuaries, auditors, and internal governance, we do not anticipate that a large majority of firms will do so.</p>
                <p>◦ We therefore estimate that <b>25% </b>(low estimate), <b>50% </b>(mid estimate), or <b>75% </b>(high estimate) of firms will seek out legal advice at a cost of <b>£30k</b>.</p>
                <p>◦ We assume that firms will process and audit all the data at the end of the three-year reporting period, as this is the most cost-effective method, and thus that the impact of this policy are best represented as a one-off cost. </p>
                <p>◦ The FCA methodology for the calculation of compliance costs usually includes an assessment of the cost of familiarisation with legislative documents, per 50 pages of legal text. However, these have not been included in this assessment because the small size of the legislative document (under 3 pages) would mean that the labour costs of familiarisation are negligible.</p>
                <p>◦ This assessment includes two areas of discretionary spend, internal governance procedures and legal advice. The policy <u>does not require</u> firms to undergo these processes in order to comply with the legislation. Rather, they have been included in this impact assessment as firms may wish to do so to confirm that their data returns comply with the requirements of the legislation. We hope to minimise firms’ need to go through these additional compliance checks at an extra cost by working with the ABI to issue industry guidance on the legislation. This will ensure that firms are fully aware of the requirements of the legislation and how to meet them effectively.</p>
                <p>◦ The calculations and final estimated one-off costs are summarised in the table in Annex 1. </p>
                <p>◦ The <b>low estimate </b>of total one-off costs is <b>£3.7million</b></p>
                <p>◦ The <b>mid/best estimate </b>of total one-off costs is <b>£4.7million</b></p>
                <p>◦ The <b>high estimate </b>of total one-off costs is <b>£5.8million</b></p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p><b>5. </b><b>Please confirm whether your measure could be subject to call-in by BRE under the following criteria. If yes, please provide a justification of why a full impact assessment is not appropriate: </b></p>
                <p>a) <b>Significant distributional impacts (such as significant transfers between different businesses or sectors) </b></p>
                <p>None</p>
                <p>b) <b>Disproportionate burdens on small businesses</b></p>
                <p>Only motor insurance providers who issue 100,000 or more private motor insurance policies in a report year will be required to provide the relevant information on costs and premiums to the FCA. This threshold was put forward for comment during the consultation period. Based on consultation responses from insurance firms and trade bodies, the threshold was raised from 10,000 to 100,000 policies in order to better protect the smallest insurers from an unfair regulatory burden. Whilst some small and specialist firms will still be captured by this threshold, HMT and the ABI are in agreement that this will not necessarily represent a disproportionate impact and that these firms should be subject to the reporting requirements. With this threshold in place, the ABI advises that the reporting requirements will still captures the vast majority (&gt;95%) of motor insurance policies sold. </p>
                <p>c) <b>Significant gross effects despite small net impacts </b></p>
                <p>None</p>
                <p>d) <b>Significant wider social, environmental, financial or economic impacts</b></p>
                <p>None</p>
                <p>e) <b>Significant novel or contentious elements </b></p>
                <p>None</p>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
